First, let's get the terms straight: &quot;soundproofing&quot; means the process of
(or materials for) keeping sound from traveling through the walls of a room,
either inbound (interfering street noises) or outbound (bothering the
neighbors). What you're after is &quot;sound treatment&quot; -- &quot;absorption&quot; or
&quot;diffusion&quot; -- to try to ameliorate the bad sound of the room.

Second, egg cartons don't work. There's an urban legend that they do,
because they visually resemble real acoustic foam, but they have little or
no effect on sound.

Third, probably the cheapest practical sound absorbing material is 6&quot; (R19)
fiberglass. It's nasty to work with, but it can help -- sometimes.

Okay, those prelims out of the way, let's do some real stuff. What are the
dimensions of your small room -- height, width and length? And what
instruments are you recording?

Peace,
Paul
