Firstly, tell the person who suggested egg cartons that they have
recommended one of the biggest bottles of snake oil going.  Egg cartons
bordering on the useless.
Secondly, &quot;soundproofing&quot; is the name that describes lowering the
transmission of sound through a boundary (e.g. walls or ceiling etc).
The word you're looking for is &quot;sound treatment&quot;.  Any sound that
remains in your room will (sooner or later) end up in a microphone.
This is what affects the quality of your recording.

OK, that's the pedantic stuff out of the way, now the questions:

1) How big is your room? (The closer the dimensions are to a cube, the
nastier the room will sound even if you have treated it)
2) Could you record in some other room that has better/different
acoustic qualities?
3) Can this room become dedicated to recording, or does it need to be
multi-function (i.e. your bedroom)?
4) What instruments are you wanting to record - acoustic or electronic?

The bottom line with sound treatment is first to create a diffuse
environment, then add absorption as required to tinker with the room's
reverberation time.

I don't know how big your room is and I don't know how much
time/effort/money you want to throw at the project, so further
recommendations will depend on what you want to achieve.

You could check out my Control Room Calculator spreadsheet that allows
you to enter the dimensions of your room, and then you can noodle around
with different wall/floor/ceiling materials to get an idea of how those
materials will change the room's acoustic properties.

http://www.whealy.com/acoustics/ControlRoom.html

