You should indeed use rubber gloves and wear a simple mask; the glass fibers
are nasty. You can buy the mask and fiberglass at a building supply store.
Depending where you are, someplace like Home Depot would work. Rubber gloves
you can get at the grocery store. You can make simple absorbers from a sheet
of 1/8&quot; chipboard, a hunk of fiberglass and some thin cloth to hold the
fiberglass in place. Don't lean or brush against them, once built.

Okay, the room. Please take some exact measurements and let us know what
they are. If the room is truly square, it's an acoustical nightmare, and you
should seriously consider working in a different space. And if the height
divides simply into the other dimensions (like an 8x10x10 room) the problem
will be worse.

Finally, if you're using both a DI and a microphone, there will be issues
even in the best room. The sound takes a certain amount of time to reach the
microphone, so that signal will be delayed with reference to the pickup/DI
setup. The best cure is usually to either ditch the DI or slide the
microphone signal backwards in a DAW until it's time-aligned with the pickup
signal.

Peace,
