More half assed solutions to a bad sounding room:

Try to randomize the surfaces of your walls, ceiling and floor.  Hang
&quot;clouds&quot; at an angle from your ceiling- wood or absorbent materials
hung from wires.  Hang shit on your walls - almost anything - shelves
with books are quite good and very useful.  The deeper (and denser)
the sound absorbent materials, the lower the frequency it will absorb.

I've always thought about getting a table saw and sawing 2 x 3's
lengthwise at an angle (45 degrees or more) and then paneling the
walls with angled wood.

I have a couple of walls with 6&quot; fiberglass hung (just nailed to the
walls), and then covered with cotton dropcloths I got at the paint
store.  This works quite well with high and mid frequencies (but
probably doesn't touch the bass).  Get the fiberglass that is enclosed
in a paper wrapper - it cuts down on the handling of the glass (and
definitely wear gloves, long sleeves and a mask).  I don't know if
it's dangerous, but if you breath this stuff in, it's makes for a few
days of scratchy uncomfortable breathing.  The little bits of glass
will embed themselves into your skin making for an itchy couple of
days.

Put down a rug with pad.

I have been trash picking for years and hanging the shit on my studio
walls.  Office cubicle panels (stacked so that they're 8 - 12&quot; deep)
work pretty well, especially when angled from the walls.  I tiled my
ceiling with layered, angled acoustic tile, sitting at progressively
farther distance from the sheetrock (using different depths of wood to
nail them to).  This works pretty good.

If you're successful in this you can make your nice room look like a
trash heap (as I did), and in the process improve the sound quality.

Then close mic instruments (see how close you need to be to cut out
room reverb, but still have enough distance from your instrument to
have a natural sound).

If you record your tracks somewhat &quot;dead&quot; (not so much ambient reverb)
you can add a longer digital reverb - making your recordings sound a
little confused, but definitely better than an overpowering tiny room.

When I think about all the work I did to make my rooms sound half way
decent I wonder why I didn't make nice bass traps, buy some ridged
fiberglass and do it right?  (answer 25 years ago when I did this they
didn't make ridged fiberglass, and I couldn't afford almost any decent
materials - and not having the internet, Ethan Winer or other
references, I was flying blind).

(Scratching my head)
Ken
