Simplest thing to try is using a good wind screen and getting very
close to the microphone, then using a suitable amount of compression
and low end roll -off EQ. If you have an omni mic with a good pop
filter, you can generally get very close and it will still sound
relatively natural.

Lots of furnishings and carpet help, so maybe try another room and not
the kitchen or the bathroom.

Acoustic treatment could be as simple as propping a few foam
mattresses up against the wall or throwing down a few rugs if you are
okay will killing the reflections a bit. Small rooms need lots of
random reflections or diffusion if you want the room to sound live,
but not too boxy. Pile in lots of furniture and stuff, at crazy
angles, keep the door open if isolation from outside noise or vise-
versa isn't a problem. Experiment!

