<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
songstressj.blogspot.com &lt;songstre ... @gmail.com&gt; wrote:
&gt;Wow, thanks for all of the great advice, everyone. So I went home and
&gt;measured the room I was in, and it turns out it is in fact 10x10x8.5.
">

This is about the worst possible configuration, because you have two big
room modes at the same frequency, and then another room mode that is right
near it.

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
&gt;If my room is actually an acoustic hell hole as suggested, would it
&gt;even be worth trying to change the sound treatment? Or should I try to
&gt;find a new room to record in?
">

You can take any room and eliminate room reflections.  The lower the
frequencies the reflections exist at, the harder and more expensive it is.
BUT, you can't take it and make the reflections sound good, and what you
really want is a room that sounds good in the first place.

I would look for a more rectangular room.  Golden mean is nice to have
although by no means essential.  Then I would sit down in the room,
clap your hands, and listen.  If you hear lots of individual discrete
reflections coming back, this is bad, and you need diffusion to break
those reflections up.  Bookcases and piles of old broken radio gear
makes for pretty good diffusion.  If you hear a lot of high frequency
slap coming back, you need high frequency absorption.  Sofas, carpets,
and stuffed animals will deal with that.

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
&gt;I am in a house, but other people live
&gt;there as well, and it's kind of hard to move around. I don't want to
&gt;just plop all of my recording equipment down in the middle of the
&gt;living room. Any suggestions?
">

If you're stuck in the room that you are in, change the room dimensions
by putting stuff in the room.  Deep bookcases on the side walls are a
good start, and room dividers and partitions can help too.  Your goal is
to break standing waves at low frequencies up, and to have enough diffusion
that high frequencies decay slowly rather than as a much of discrete
echoes, and enough absorption that there isn't more high frequency room
sound than low frequency room sound.

The various commercial acoustical control products can do this effectively
without looking silly.  If you don't mind the room looking silly, you can
deal with a lot of the problems in less expensive ways.  However, it may
result in losing a lot more working space in the room.
--scott
