<POSTDATE> 2007-08-14T12:50:00 </POSTDATE>
<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
songstressj.blogspot.com wrote:
&gt; Wow, thanks for all of the great advice, everyone. So I went home and measured the room I was in, and it turns out it is in fact 10x10x8.5.
&gt; If my room is actually an acoustic hell hole as suggested, would it even be worth trying to change the sound treatment?
">

A room that is cube-like will resonate very strongly at the frequency
that corresponds to the room's width (which is also happens to be its
length and height).  In your case, for a 10x10x8.5 room, you'll hear
boominess in a two octave range centred roughly on the A an octave below
middle C.  The notes that appear to boom the most will be A's (or there
abouts).

The trick to improving the acoustics in a room is first to use
diffusion, and then to apply absorption.  Diffusion scatters the sound
and helps break up strong echoes and makes the room feel like it is
filled with sound.  As Don suggested, the easiest way to do this is to
go down to your nearest carpet dealer, and ask for the old cardboard
tubes around which the carpet is wrapped. Get as many as you can and if
you can get a variety of diameters, so much the better.

Then simply lean them against the walls every 2' or so and try another
recording.  You'll notice that when you sing, you will feel far more
surrounded by sound, which in turn will help you sing better (this
effect is known as &quot;listener envelopement&quot; - even though you're the
performer).  If the room is still too live (or echoey), then try hanging
some heavy curtains to act as absorbers.

If this room can be dedicated to recording, then it would be worth
cutting the tubes in half down their length, and fixing them more
permanently to the walls.  That way they won't fall over if you bump
into them.  You could even try hanging the curtains in front of the tubes.

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
&gt; Or should I try to find a new room to record in?
">

Depends if the proposed solution is acceptable to you or not and whether
or not you have another room available to you.

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
&gt; I am in a house, but other people live there as well, and it's kind of hard to move around. I don't want to just plop all of my recording equipment down in the middle of the living room.
">

Fair enough.  However, if you don't mind moving your equipment around,
and the other people don't mind if the living room is temporarily
hi-jacked, then you might find that a workable solution.

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
&gt; Any suggestions? And if I really do need to move rooms, any suggestions on ideal dimensions?
">

If you are able to construct your own room, then choose dimensions that
have no common divisor.  E.G. 9' x 14' x 17' (HxWxL)

