Paul I know you think the egg carton trick is an urban myth but let me
describe what I have done.
I have a very small house in a rural town. Most houses around here were
built pre 1940. Good solid structures but small with very small rooms. In
the northern tier so keeping the warmth in was the priority.
On the main floor I have a room that is 7'X10'. I lined the walls with the
paper formed egg catrons, blew an absorbant coating made from latex paint
and a fibre'd support medium with one of those textured material air hoppers
that they use on stucco houses. I positioned bass traps in the cornors and
am currently considering installing a softer overhead.
The room filters out the street noise (one vehical an hour tops till 7pm
then silent) plus keeps the sound of a recording session inside.
On the two windows in the room I have a roll each fashioned to the window
top that is thick padded quilt material.
To say that egg crates are a myth is irresponsible. It has a great deal to
do with how the installation is preformed and what properties you are taking
advantage of. For instance my set up has the egg cup section mounted onto
the crate top section, doubling the cardboard. Then the textured coating
that is applied on top of that has it's own abosorbant and diffusive
properties.
I have been considering draping a sheet of black cloth over it as well, but
as long as the drunks stay off the walls it functions like a dream fo my
recording.
